"circa 1603","about 1600":"circa 1600","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1595":"1595","about 1599":"circa 1599","1605":"1605","1649":"1649","about 1570":"circa 1570","1603":"1603","Willoughby, Warwickshire, England":"Willoughby, Warwickshire, England","England":"Verenigd Koninkrijk","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Westminster, Middlesex, England":"Westminster, Middlesex, England"},"en":{"about 1570–":"about 1570–Deceased","–1610":"–1610","1591–1649":"1591–1649","1594–Male":"1594–Deceased","1595–1655":"1595–1655","1599–Female":"1599–Deceased","1600–Female":"1600–Deceased","1603–Female":"1603–Deceased","1605–Female":"1605–Deceased","1570–Female":"1570–Deceased","14 June 1591":"14 June 1591","1594":"1594","1571":"1571","1570":"1570","1591":"1591","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1600":"1600","1655":"1655","about 1605":"about 1605","1599":"1599","1610":"1610","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","about 1603":"about 1603","about 1600":"about 1600","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1595":"1595","about 1599":"about 1599","1605":"1605","1649":"1649","about 1570":"about 1570","1603":"1603","Willoughby, Warwickshire, England":"Willoughby, Warwickshire, England","England":"United Kingdom","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Westminster, Middlesex, England":"Westminster, Middlesex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived on or by a hill, from Middle English <i>hill</i>, <i>hell</i>, <i>hull</i> ‘hill’ (Old English <i>hyll</i>). Compare   Hiller  . This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English: possibly in some cases from the personal name <i>Hille</i>, a pet form of some name such as   Hilger   or   Hillary  .","German: from a short form of   Hildebrand   or any of a variety of other names, male and female, containing ancient Germanic <i>hild</i> ‘battle’ as the first element."],"variants":[{"name":"Hillock","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) small hill’, from Middle English <i>hillok</i>, a diminutive of <i>hille</i> (Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’). See   Hill  ."]},{"name":"Hills","meanings":["English: variant of   Hill   with genitival <i>-s</i> if a relationship name, attested in Matilda <i>Hilles</i>, 1327 (Somerset), where the genitival form may signify widowhood; or with plural <i>-s</i> if habitational, attested in Johanne <i>de Hyles</i>, 1379 (Bickerstaffe, Lancashire), and Ricardo <i>del Hyles</i>, 1379 (Great Eccleston, Lancashire); or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, probably the most common form."]},{"name":"Hiller","meanings":["German: metronymic from <i>Hille</i>, a pet form of the female personal name <i>Hildegund</i> (see   Hilke  ).","German: from a masculine personal beginning with the ancient Germanic element <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German: variant of <b>Hüller</b> (see   Huller  )."]},{"name":"Hil","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hill  .","Dutch (<b>Van den Hil</b>): topographic name from <i>hil, hul</i> ‘hill’, particularly in the sense of a <i>flight hill</i> above sea level in the southwestern Netherlands."]}]},{"name":"Isabell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705206,"age":1,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":15,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":50,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705213,"age":72,"year":"1642","toYear":"1651","julianDay":2320789,"title":"The English Civil War","description":"A series of conflicts regarding England's governance during the years 1642 to 1651 is now known as The English Civil War. Charles I summoned supporters to join him against his enemies in Parliament. In October 1642, nearly 10,000 men fought for Charles I and chased Parliament across the River Tamar. Fighting continued for years and was finally ended at the Battle of Worcester on September 3, 1651, with a Parliamentarian victory.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705216,"age":118,"year":"1688","toYear":"1689","julianDay":2337590,"title":"Glorious Revolution","description":"The Glorious Revolution brought the downfall of Catholic King James II and the reign of his Protestant daughter Mary and her Dutch husband, William III of Orange.","url":"http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/british/civil_war_revolution/glorious_revolution_01.shtml","urlTitle":"BBC - Glorious Revolution","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Isabell Hill was born about 1570. She had at least 2 sons and 5 daughters with John Treadway. She died in Westminster, Middlesex, England."},"et":{"about 1570–":"umbes 1570–Surnud","–1610":"–1610","1591–1649":"1591–1649","1594–Male":"1594–Surnud","1595–1655":"1595–1655","1599–Female":"1599–Surnud","1600–Female":"1600–Surnud","1603–Female":"1603–Surnud","1605–Female":"1605–Surnud","1570–Female":"1570–Surnud","14 June 1591":"14. juuni 1591","1594":"1594","1571":"1571","1570":"1570","1591":"1591","1689":"1689","1688":"1688","1600":"1600","1655":"1655","about 1605":"umbes 1605","1599":"1599","1610":"1610","1642":"1642","1620":"1620","about 1603":"umbes 1603","about 1600":"umbes 1600","1651":"1651","1585":"1585","1595":"1595","about 1599":"umbes 1599","1605":"1605","1649":"1649","about 1570":"umbes 1570","1603"